children.subject:
Ya if you take 168 in the fall...

Professor Scott doesn't webcast, and I personally have to also read lecture slides after attending lecture, simply because a lot of the vocabulary is new to me. Each lecture has around 80 slides as well, so depending on your speed, i'd say reviewing a lecture can take 1-2 hours. The cool thing is that the concepts relate to each other, so there's always a big picture to a lecture and thus it'll become easier to learn new material as you progress and gain better insight on past lectures.

There's 1 discussion per week. There's no homework. There's vitamins every lecture, graded by completion not correctness and it's basically multiple choice. If you take the time to complete, could take 10 min. If you want to put random answers, I suppose it takes like 5 seconds lol. Also a lost section every week. I've only been able to attend one, and it was great.

There are 2 projects. We've only done 1 so far. That 1 project, we had 3 weeks to complete. I wanna say the total # of lines coded was maybe 50 max? It might have been less or a bit more? It's kinda like a 61A project, filling in a function. If you worked with people and went to office hours when stuck, it shouldn't take too much time. It's not easy...but it's really doable, especially if you start early.

1 midterm, 1 final.

For EE128, there's a problem set every week, which takes a good chunk of time, maybe 3 hours per pset, but this may differ with Prof. Sojoudi. Lab reports can take some time since they are not hand written. If you don't go prepared to labs, or the prelab isn't correct, lab can become more time consuming, so diligence is due. Even on the days I had managed to finish early, I had about 30 minutes left for labs, but this might just be me being a bit slower. I'd estimate the lab reports taking about time comparable to the psets.
